content.description: Stand start on the big sidepull and the huge foothold. Move right into Tonya Harding.
content.location: 10 feet left of Tonya Harding on the big rock to your left on the approach to Tin Man

content.description:
Really fun traverse, from right to left, on good holds, and with a couple of long reaches.

Worth laying the pads down for, the movement is really fun.
content.location: On the way up to Tin Man, you'll pass a huge rock face just uphill of the river. The seams on the tall right face are Seams Dangerous, and the lowball traverse to the left is Tonya Harding. Start low, on the right side, sitting, and traverse left up to the big jug above. It's a drop off problem.

content.description: The sit start variation. Start on the wacky sloper feature and a good right hand edge. Make some thuggy moves into the stand start position, huck to the slot, and do an easy top out. I started sitting on the tree root which made it a lil' easier to haul off the ground.
content.location: Same as Tin Man Stand. Follow the trail up until you see a fat overhanging bloc. The left arete is Tin Man

content.description: Start with a left hand on the arete and a right on a good side pull.  Work up to some interesting holds and a nice top out.  Seemed pretty solid for the grade.
content.location: Just to the right of the tree.  Cant miss it

content.description: Start in the same vicinity as The Slot, and traverse left, and upwards, on bad feet, and good crimps to an easy topout. Good stone, but not the most exciting line in the world.
content.location: Left of The Slot on the left side of the Tin Man

content.description: Starting on the thin rail, work up and right to the two incut slots in the face
content.protection: 2 pads might be nice, a bit of an uneven landing
content.location: Just to the left of the tree hugging the boulder

content.description: One my favorite high balls in Leavenworth. Start with big moves on decent holds, then find a committing crux at the 15 foot mark, over a sloping, airy landing. It's easy to imagine falling down the hill into the river below. Really fun.
content.protection: Pads and a good spotter. Try hard not to fall off the crux; it could be pretty bad.
content.location: As you are walking up the hill to Tin Man and Spanish Trav, you'll notice this wall on your left. It's got seams overlapping the whole way up, with a sloper topout at the 20 foot mark, and 10 feet of easy climbing above it. Look for a large Ponderosa at the top.

content.description: Start as far left as you want, climb up the fin to the right. Top out at the apex. Both aretes are on. Fun warmup.
content.protection: A couple pads. The landing is a little rocky
content.location: Obvious free standing shark fin to the left of Tin Man

content.description: Start sitting on the lower corner matched on the lip or with a low undercling jug. Slap up the blunt, low corner to a wide rock-over move for and edge on the face. Very silly, and pretty fun too.
content.location: The front right corner of the Tin Man boulder. Squeezed between two other small boulders.

content.description:
A cool line on great holds, with one long reach. The face has a lot of growth on it, but these holds felt solid. I thought the greenery added to the aesthetic. There are a bunch of ways to climb the face on the right, but I think this is now the most obvious, as climbers have warmed up here long enough to have beaten back the vegetation in the best spots.

It's not a jungle climb, just a nice climb with green around the holds.
content.protection: 1 pad, a spot would be nice for the more committing move to the lip.
content.location: Around the right corner from Tin Man.
